sec.p:
Figure 4 illustrates the control system designed for the five-level rectifier, which processes the input signals $V_{g}$ (grid voltage), $I_{g}$ (grid current), and $V_{D C}$ (DC link voltage). A delay block is incorporated to extract the orthogonal component, known as the $\beta$-axis. This $\beta$-axis signal is then input into a PLL, which monitors the phase angle of the supply voltage and generates the reference current for the source. The control architecture consists of two loops: an outer loop that regulates the DC link voltage and an inner loop that controls the grid current. The PLL uses the delayed $\beta$-axis signal to accurately synchronize with the grid, ensuring proper phase tracking and reference generation. This dual-loop control structure enables effective management of both voltage stability and current flow from the grid. The average grid current can be calculated as follows:
\begin{align*}
& L \frac{d i_{g}}{d t}=V_{g}-r i_{g}-V_{a b} \\
& =V_{g}-r i_{g}-d V_{D C_{r e f}} \tag{1}
\end{align*}

The above equation (1) can be transformed into Laplace by taking grid voltage ($V_{g}$) constant, and averaged value of duty cycle and current.
\begin{equation*}
L s i_{g}=-r i_{g}-d V_{D C_{r e f}} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

Fig. 5:

Control technique for psfb converter

The transfer function obtained from reference value of DC voltage ($V_{D C_{\text {ref }}}$) shows that the grid current depends on output DC voltage, value of inductor and line impedance.
\begin{equation*}
\frac{i_{g}}{d}=\frac{-V_{D C_{r e f}}}{L_{s}+r} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

To regulate the DC link voltage outer loop is examined as
\begin{align*}
i_{g} & =i_{c e q}+i_{D C} \\
C_{e q} \frac{d V}{d t} & =i_{g}-i_{D C} \tag{4}
\end{align*}
Where $C_{e q}$ is equivalent value of capacitor connected in parallel and $i_{D C}$ is output DC current. Figure 5 illustrates the control system used for the PSFB converter. This system employs two PI controllers to determine the appropriate duty cycle for the DC-DC converter's operation. To compute the reference charging current for the battery ($I_{o}^{*}$), the error between the desired battery voltage and the actual measured voltage is processed through a PI controller. The resulting value defines the reference charging current as:
\begin{equation*}
I_{o}^{*}=K_{p}\left(V_{o r e f}-V_{o}\right)+\frac{K_{i}}{s}\left(V_{o r e f}-V_{o}\right) \tag{5}
\end{equation*}

Here $K_{p}$ and $K_{i}$ represent the proportional and integral gains of the controller, respectively. $V_{o_{r e f}}$ denotes the reference voltage for the battery, while Vo indicates the actual output voltage. The computed reference charging current is then used to determine the duty cycle required for the PSFB converter to achieve constant current (CC) charging, as described in equation (6).
\begin{equation*}
d=K_{p}\left(I_{o}^{*}-I_{o}\right)+\frac{K_{i}}{s}\left(I_{o}^{*}-I_{o}\right) \tag{6}
\end{equation*}

The conduction losses depend on switch current (RMS) $I_{r m s}$ and the resistance (on state), $R_{D S(O N)}$ as shown
\begin{equation*}
P_{\text {conduction(mosfet) }}=R_{D S(O N)}\left(T_{J}\right) I_{r m s}^{2} \tag{7}
\end{equation*}

The variation in $R_{D S(O N)}$ with respect to junction temperature $T_{J}$ is taken into account. The estimation of switching losses follows Infineon's guidelines, as shown in equation (8)–(9) [31]. When a MOSFET is turned on, its body diode continues conducting while the current increases. To turn off the MOSFET, the minority carriers stored in the body diode must be cleared, which involves absorbing reverse recovery energy-leading to additional power loss. This loss, quantified using the reverse recovery charge ($Q_{R R}$), can be obtained from the component datasheet and is used in the power dissipation calculations [12].
\begin{equation*}
P_{S W(O N)}=\left(V_{D S} I_{O N} \frac{T_{r t}+T_{f t}}{2}+Q_{R R} V_{D S}\right) F_{S W} \tag{8}
\end{equation*}

In the context of MOSFET turn-off behaviour, several key parameters are considered: VDS indicates the drain-to-source voltage, ION is the drain current at the moment switching begins, $T_{r t}$ represents the current rise time, Tft corresponds to the voltage fall time, and $Q_{R R}$ refers to the reverse recovery charge.
\begin{equation*}
P_{S W(O F F)}=\left(V_{D S} I_{O F F} \frac{T_{f t}+T_{r u r}}{2}+Q_{R R} V_{D S}\right) F_{S W} \tag{9}
\end{equation*}

The junction temperature of a MOSFET can be estimated using the thermal impedance provided in the datasheet. This information can then be used to calculate the total power loss.
\begin{equation*}
P_{L O S S}=P_{\text {conduction }(\text { mosfet })}+P_{S W(O N)}+P_{S W(O F F)} \tag{10}
\end{equation*}

The power loss in an inductor depends on its equivalent series resistance (ESR) RESR due to its significant effect.
\begin{equation*}
P_{L O S S}=I_{L, R M S}^{2} R_{L, E S R} \tag{11}
\end{equation*}

Dielectric loss in capacitors is often neglected in favour of considering power loss caused by equivalent series resistance (ESR), which significantly affects performance at higher frequencies.
\begin{equation*}
P_{L O S S}=I_{C, R M S}^{2} R_{C, E S R} \tag{12}
\end{equation*}

Fig. 6:

Loss calculation of the charging system

The high frequency transformer system experiences two distinct forms of loss: loss due to conduction in both the primary and secondary windings, as well as core loss. The calculation of conduction loss is
\begin{equation*}
P_{T, \text { cond }}=I_{R M S, \text { pri }}^{2} R_{\text {pri }}+I_{R M S, \text { sec }}^{2} R_{\text {sec }} \tag{13}
\end{equation*}

The flux density in the core varies in magnitude based on the voltage applied to the primary side. In this case, the voltage waveform is approximately square-shaped. Notably, the isolation transformer is constructed using an RM14 core made of 3C95 ferrite material and Litz wire.
\begin{gather*}
P_{T, \text { core }}=\frac{V K_{i} \Delta \beta^{\beta-\alpha}}{T_{S W}} \sum_{m}\left|\frac{B_{m+1}-B_{m}}{t_{m+1}-t_{m}}\right\vert\left(t_{m+1}-t_{m}\right) \tag{14}\\
P_{\text {loss }}=P_{\text {cond }}+P_{\text {core }} \tag{15}
\end{gather*}
